# {{VAULT_NAME}}

A local knowledge graph built from meeting transcripts. A dictation tool (e.g.
Handy, a local speech-to-text app) types transcribed speech directly into a
new note in `00-Inbox/`, or you paste in a transcript from Teams/Zoom/
Granola/etc. A daily pipeline enriches, tags, and links notes into a growing
Obsidian graph, using Claude Code as the only thing that ever touches note
content over the network.

Scaffolded by [meeting-graph](https://github.com/AndyMDH/meeting-graph).

## Getting started (day one)

1. **Open the vault** in Obsidian: `open -a Obsidian {{VAULT_PATH}}` (or open
   normally afterwards — Obsidian remembers it). New notes (`Cmd+N`) are
   already configured to land in `00-Inbox/` (see `.obsidian/app.json`).
2. **Set up your dictation tool** (Handy or similar): grant it Microphone,
   Accessibility, and Input Monitoring permission in System Settings →
   Privacy & Security. Without Accessibility/Input Monitoring, a global
   hotkey may appear to fire but nothing gets typed. If your tool supports a
   toggle/hands-free recording mode (start with one press, stop with
   another, rather than holding a key down), turn it on in its own Settings
   UI — much nicer for meeting-length dictation.
3. **Capture a meeting**: `Cmd+N` in Obsidian → click into the note body →
   trigger your dictation tool → talk → stop it → save (Obsidian autosaves).
   Use **one note per meeting**, not a single running daily note — the
   pipeline treats one inbox file as one meeting/topic.
4. **Run the pipeline** on demand: `{{VAULT_PATH}}/90-System/run.sh` (add the
   alias below for convenience). It also runs automatically once a day if you
   load the launchd job (see "Running the pipeline").
5. **Check the result** in `10-Meetings/` — frontmatter, tags, a structured
   summary, and your original transcript preserved underneath. Add to your
   shell profile:
   ```bash
   alias {{ALIAS_NAME}}="{{VAULT_PATH}}/90-System/run.sh"
   ```
   You'll also get a macOS notification when a run finishes, summarizing what
   it did (see "Running the pipeline").

## Quick capture (skip opening Obsidian first)

`90-System/quick-capture.sh` creates a new timestamped file directly in
`00-Inbox/` and opens it in Obsidian — same result as `Cmd+N`, runnable from
anywhere without switching apps first. If you've set up Templater's folder
template (see "Customizing" below), it still fires on files created this way,
since it watches the folder, not the app that created the file.

To bind it to a global hotkey (GUI-only step, can't be scripted):

1. Open **Shortcuts.app** → new shortcut → add action **"Run Shell Script"** →
   set it to run `{{VAULT_PATH}}/90-System/quick-capture.sh` with `/bin/bash`.
2. In the shortcut's detail pane, click **Add Keyboard Shortcut** and set
   whatever combo you want free system-wide.

## Folder structure

```
{{VAULT_NAME}}/
  00-Inbox/            raw transcripts land here; pipeline consumes from here
    duplicates/        inbox files detected as duplicates of existing meeting notes
  10-Meetings/         enriched meeting notes (pipeline output)
  20-Wikis/            synthesized research-area pages (hub nodes)
  30-Tags/             one note per tag = the tag registry
  90-System/
    logs/              per-run pipeline logs (rotated, 30 day retention)
    templates/         note templates
    pipeline.log       append-only human-readable run history
    run.sh             orchestration script
  .claude/
    skills/
      meeting-enricher/  enriches inbox notes into structured, tagged meeting notes
      wiki-builder/      synthesizes wiki hub pages once a topic has enough sources
```

## Why it's structured this way

- **Tags as notes** (`30-Tags/`) make every tag a visible node in Obsidian's
  graph, and give the agent a canonical, greppable registry it can read
  before tagging. This is the main defense against tag sprawl: the agent can
  only apply a tag that already exists as a file, and creating a new one is a
  deliberate, logged act.
- **Wikis as hub nodes** (`20-Wikis/`): once a topic accumulates enough
  meeting notes, `wiki-builder` synthesizes a single page that many meetings
  link into. Without this, the graph is a hairball of meeting-to-meeting
  links; with it, wikis become readable hubs surrounded by their source
  meetings.
- **Numbered top-level folders** (`00-`, `10-`, `20-`...) keep the pipeline
  stages and Obsidian's file browser in a consistent, sortable order.

Your seed tag registry starts close to empty (just the system `fragment`
tag) plus whatever starter tags you chose during install. Add real tags that
match your own domain before your first real meeting — the registry only
works as a sprawl-defense if it actually reflects your world.

## Running the pipeline

Manual run:

```bash
{{VAULT_PATH}}/90-System/run.sh
```

The pipeline can also run automatically once a day via launchd (see
`90-System/com.meeting-graph.pipeline.plist`, installed at
`~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.meeting-graph.pipeline.plist` if you chose to
load it during install):

```bash
# load (start scheduling)
launchctl load ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.meeting-graph.pipeline.plist

# unload (stop scheduling)
launchctl unload ~/Library/LaunchAgents/com.meeting-graph.pipeline.plist

# trigger one run immediately, outside the schedule
launchctl start local.meeting-graph.pipeline
```

If the machine is asleep at the scheduled time, launchd runs the missed job
on next wake (default `StartCalendarInterval` behavior) — no special handling
needed.

Logs:
- `90-System/pipeline.log` — one line per meaningful event (file processed,
  tag created, wiki created/updated, empty-inbox skip, git sync).
- `90-System/logs/run-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS.log` — full Claude Code output per run,
  retained 30 days.
- `90-System/logs/launchd.log` — stdout/stderr from launchd invocations.

Every run also fires a macOS notification ("N meetings enriched" or "Inbox
empty - nothing to process"), summarized from the pipeline.log lines that run
just appended — so you don't need to check logs to know a run happened.

## Syncing to a git remote (optional)

`run.sh` auto-detects whether this vault is the root of its own git repo with
an `origin` remote configured, and if so, commits and pushes anything dirty
at the end of each run (including manual edits you made outside the
pipeline). If you never run `git init` here, this step silently no-ops — no
setup required unless you want it.

**Important gotcha**: `git init` this folder specifically, don't assume it's
already a repo. If your home directory (or some parent folder) happens to be
under git, commands run from inside this vault will silently resolve to
*that* repo instead — meaning a commit here could sweep in unrelated files
from way outside the vault. Always confirm with:

```bash
cd {{VAULT_PATH}} && git rev-parse --show-toplevel
```

This should print `{{VAULT_PATH}}` itself. If it prints something else (like
your home directory), run `git init` inside the vault to give it its own
repo before turning on sync. `run.sh`'s sync step already checks for this and
refuses to sync if the vault isn't its own repo root, but it's worth knowing
why.

If you do set this up, use a **private** repo unless you're comfortable with
meeting content being public — this vault will contain real transcripts.

## Obsidian configuration

### Graph view — color by topic

Not automated (it depends on which tags you actually accumulate), but once
you have real notes, set up **Graph view → Groups** (sidebar icon, or `Cmd+P`
→ "Open graph view", then the filter/groups panel) to color nodes by topic
instead of by pipeline stage — this is what actually makes topic clusters
readable, more so than coloring by folder:

1. Pick your ~7-8 most-used tags from `30-Tags/`.
2. Add one `colorGroups` rule per tag: query `tag:#<tagname>`, one distinct
   hue each (`.obsidian/graph.json` is plain JSON — editing it directly is
   easier than the settings UI for more than 2-3 groups).
3. If you have a "low-signal" meta-tag (e.g. something like `fragment` for
   short notes that aren't real topics), give it a muted gray and put its rule
   **last** in the array — later entries win when a note matches more than
   one tag, so this keeps low-signal notes visually receding instead of
   competing with real topic colors.
4. Stop at ~8 hues even if you have more tags — beyond that, distinct colors
   stop being visually distinguishable anyway. Leave less-used tags uncolored
   (default) rather than forcing a 9th hue; promote one once it's actually
   active.

Wiki pages (`20-Wikis/`) and tag notes (`30-Tags/`) don't carry a `tags`
frontmatter field, so they won't match any of these rules and stay uncolored
— which reads as intended: a topic's meeting notes light up in that topic's
color and visually surround their uncolored wiki hub, making the hub-and-spoke
shape legible without a separate, competing "this is a hub" color.

- **Core plugins**: Backlinks, Graph view, Templates. No community plugins
  required for the pipeline itself.
  - Optional later: Dataview (dashboards over frontmatter), Juggl (richer
    graph interaction).
- **Templates plugin**: point at `90-System/templates/` if you want to draft
  notes manually using the same shape the pipeline produces.
- **Optional: auto-timestamp inbox captures.** `90-System/templates/inbox-capture.md`
  is shipped for this but not wired up automatically — it needs the
  [Templater](https://silentvoid13.github.io/Templater/) community plugin
  (Settings → Community plugins, turn off Restricted Mode first). In
  Templater's settings: set "Templates folder location" to
  `90-System/templates`, enable "Folder templates", and add a rule mapping
  `00-Inbox` → `90-System/templates/inbox-capture.md`. Skippable —
  `meeting-enricher` infers the date itself either way. `.gitignore` excludes
  `.obsidian/plugins/` so plugin code never gets vendored into the vault's git
  history.

### iCloud / sync warning

If this vault lives in iCloud Drive, background sync can conflict with the
pipeline writing/moving files mid-run (partial uploads, conflicted copies).
Prefer a plain local folder, backed up via git (see above) or Obsidian Sync,
rather than parking the vault directly under iCloud Drive.

## Tag registry rules (enforced by `meeting-enricher`)

The filenames in `30-Tags/` are the only permitted tags. New tags are
exceptional and require all of:
1. No existing tag covers the concept, even loosely.
2. The concept is central to the note (would appear in a one-sentence
   summary).
3. At least 2 other plausible future notes would use it.

Every new tag creation is logged to `90-System/pipeline.log` as
`NEW TAG: <tag> - <justification>` for periodic review.
